<TEXT>
californias first execution in 23 
years may be less than a week away and some surveys suggest that 
80 percent of the states residents think its about time 
but theres a small vocal minority trying to change the hearts 
and minds of those who believe that death is the proper punishment 
for taking a human life 
at 3 am on april 3 unless appeals are successful 37yearold 
robert alton harris will be strapped into san quentins 
7squarefoot applegreen gas chamber and a cloud of cyanide gas 
will end his troubled life 
state attorneys in san diego on tuesday filed their response to 
harris federal appeal saying there is nothing new in the latest 
petition to warrant a stay of execution 
harris attorneys were to reply wednesday and a hearing was 
scheduled for then if us district judge william enright rejects 
their stay request the defense lawyers next move would be to file 
a petition with the 9th us circuit court of appeals a denial at 
the 9th circuit would leave only an appeal to the us supreme 
court which has denied harris appeals four times 
jim young of oakland is conducting a threeweek vigil outside 
the prison 
should we as a society use the same language as the murderer 
the language of death and create new victims society must rise 
above the level of the murderer said young 
on monday young a member of death penalty focus sat by a 
black cardboard coffin and signs reading dont kill for me and 
the death penalty is dead wrong 
two other people including the wife of another deathrow 
inmate stood nearby 
also on hand were a man and a woman who declined to identify 
themselves carrying signs applauding the execution and urging 
people to remember his victims 
on tuesday roman catholic priests from around the state led a 
prayer service outside the main gate against the execution four 
capital punishment foes were arrested for blocking a road 
authorities said 
harris on parole after a manslaughter conviction was sentenced 
to die for the 1978 murders of san diego 16yearolds john mayeski 
and michael baker he abducted them at a burger stand to use their 
car in a bank robbery 
we know were up against a hard rock of public opinion but 
people say theyre for the death penalty because its been sold 
to them said young burned by the sun and slightly weak from the 
early stages of a 10day fast 
thats why were out here at the gate to give out 
information 
members of other groups opposed to capital punishment also have 
been fasting speaking out taking turns in the vigil and writing 
to gov george deukmejian asking for clemency 
in london on tuesday about 30 members of amnesty international 
protested outside the us embassy the human rights organization 
left a letter for the ambassador expressing concern that there will 
be a precedent created for other american states not currently 
carrying out executions 
death penalty foes also fear harris execution could be quickly 
followed by many others in california more than 270 other men are 
on san quentins death row prosecutors discount such a possibility 
because each prisoner gets the same appeals that have helped delay 
harris execution for 11 years 
opponents argue that capital punishment is immoral is not a 
deterrent and is a poor way to convince people that murder is wrong 
yet the san franciscobased field institute which conducts the 
california poll found in mid1986 that 83 percent of californians 
supported capital punishment and 14 percent were opposed 
california law provides for life without possibility of parole 
but some people are skeptical it assures murderers wont be 
released to kill again 
whats to say the people of the state of california wont 
elect another jerry brown into office and end up with a parole 
board to let those people out said steve baker a policeman and 
the father of one of harris young victims 
brown the state democratic party leader is a former governor 
known for his liberal judicial appointments 
michael rushford president of the criminal justice legal 
foundation a national victims rights group based in sacramento 
argued that sentencing murderers to life without parole does not 
assure they will not kill other prisoners or guards 
rushford maintains theres little risk of executing an innocent 
man 
the chances of an innocent person being convicted of a serious 
crime in this country is many many times less than the chance of 
being murdered he said 
</TEXT>
