<TEXT>
us capitol police officials cope with 
terrorist threats tourists and foreign leaders but their toughest 
current challenge may be allegations of racism aired by their own 
black officers 
the accusations have left the police force racially polarized 
black officers have accused top commanders all white of 
discrimination the police brass has denied the allegations and 
white officers have backed their superiors 
blacks brought their grievances to a house hearing last week 
appearing in such large numbers that a police security detail 
normally would have been assigned to crowd control 
this time it wasnt necessary because the orderly spectators 
and key witnesses at the house administration subcommittee 
hearing were the police 
rep mary rose oakar dohio chairwoman of the police 
subcommittee promised after hearing from both sides that reforms 
were coming to ease the tension she urged a constructive 
dialogue between the black officers and chief frank a kerrigan 
the police force that guards the capitol complex has 1238 
officers including 336 blacks 27 percent of the force 
however the top ranks of lieutenant captain inspector deputy 
chief assistant chief and chief include 61 whites and four blacks 
a minority percentage of 62 percent 
house sergeantatarms jack russ a member of the threeman 
capitol police board said that before an objective written test 
was instituted in 1983 the department was a good old boy 
network with car pool promotions 
but thats been changed said russ who serves on the 
governing board with senate sergeantatarms henry giugni and 
architect of the capitol george white 
sgt ronald l richardson executive director of the newly 
organized capitol police chapter of the national black police 
association said cronyism and nepotism still exist in 
promotions assignments and training for advancement 
we do not have a single black in a policy or decisionmaking 
position above the rank of captain he said 
blacks who apply for top positions are told vacancies have been 
filled only to later learn the person selected for the position 
was handpicked richardson said soon it also comes to light 
that the person selected had been chosen prior to the official 
announcement of the job vacancy 
and why richardson demanded to know were several black 
officers fired after being accused of drug use while white 
officers similarly accused were allowed to remain on the force 
chief kerrigan said he was unaware of those cases and has told 
richardson to provide him a list of specific examples of 
discrimination 
i wont stand for any type of discrimination whatsoever if it 
was brought to my attention i would do something about it i asked 
for a third party to investigate if theres any discrimination 
im unaware of it kerrigan said 
russ added there may be racism in this department if there 
is racism where is it come back with a list of your problems we 
never had one complaint until a couple of weeks ago 
a number of white police officers including several women 
wrote the subcommittee to deny any discrimination 
as a female caucasian official on the united states capitol 
police force i do not feel that there is a problem with 
discrimination wrote sgt ruth b micer she recalled using her 
vacation to study for written and oral tests she regarded as fair 
to everyone 
another letter by lts price s goldston and stanley j 
grochowski jr both white added we have no knowledge of racial 
discrimination existing within the united states capitol police 
kerrigan said the best way to make room for blacks at the top is 
to create a new retirement system currently top white officers 
stay at their jobs because they must work 30 years and be age 55 or 
older to qualify for retirement longer than in other local police 
departments 
the chief proposed a system to allow retirement at age 50 after 
20 years of service or after 25 years of service regardless of age 
</TEXT>
