<TEXT>
labor leaders call walkouts at 37 nuclear 
power plants a success as workers made a bid for union 
representation but companies involved say insignificant numbers of 
workers stayed off the job 
about 3000 radiation technicians at nuclear reactors across the 
nation closed for refueling were encouraged to walk off the job 
monday in a nationwide effort to have the international brotherhood 
of electrical workers become their bargaining agent 
all i can tell you is its working said ibew official av 
griffies who said it was impossible to say how many of the 3000 
technicians involved refused to go to work monday 
but several utility contractors said the walkouts had little 
impact at the reactors where they provide workers to monitor 
radiation levels 
it has been business as usual said karen armour a 
spokeswoman at asca brown boveri inc of stamford conn the 
parent of power systems energy services inc 
the company has more than 600 technicians working at nine sites 
very few workers failed to show she said 
frank ingram a spokesman for the nuclear regulatory commission 
said the agency had been monitoring the situation and had not 
received any reports that work at the closed reactors had stopped 
griffies said striking workers set up only one picket line at 
the turkey point nuclear plant south of miami where about 100 
workers stayed off the job 
another 100 contract workers at florida power corps crystal 
river nuclear plant refused to work 
griffies declined to elaborate on why only one picket line was 
established or to say how long the walkout would last 
the ibew which already represents the majority of permanent 
nuclear power plant workers targeted eight utility contractors who 
provide traveling health physics technicians to reactors that 
close down for refueling or maintenance 
those technicians make between 11 and 14 an hour and have not 
received pay increases in eight years griffies said 
james p schmitt spokesman for westinghouse electric corp in 
pittsburgh said the strike is not having an impact with the 
westinghouse workers in the industry 
the call for the job action has had little or no impact 
schmitt said 
between 300 to 500 westinghouse technicians are involved he 
said the company has a pool of 1000 workers he said 
schmitt said substantial majority of technicians were on the 
job but weve had a couple here and there that have called in 
sick the numbers are insignificant so its conceivable that their 
illnesses are legitimate 
baltimore gas and electric co spokesman art sluzark said the 
strike had not affected the companys calvert cliffs nuclear power 
plant 
all 98 of the technicians who work for bartlett nuclear of 
plymouth mass reported for work monday he said 
