<TEXT>
an agriculture department trade report says 
the united states may gain some of the foreign vegetable oil market 
for rapeseed and canola but probably will take a back seat to 
canada as a major supplier 
more and more us farmers are interested in getting on the 
rapeseed bandwagon the report said now even nontraditional 
growing areas are getting excited about the prospect of growing 
rapeseed 
although the report uses the term rapeseed generically to 
include canola it does explain the distinction between the two 
crops modified versions of rapeseed developed in canada are 
recognized as canola 
the report in the april issue of agexporter magazine said 
there are no official usda figures on rapeseed production although 
industry estimates are in the range of 65000 to 100000 acres of 
socalled doubleo or canolatype seed and 10000 to 20000 acres 
of industrialgrade rapeseed 
plant geneticist dick auld of the university of idaho who 
pioneered much of the current research in rapeseed varieties for 
us cultivation said most of the increase is expected to occur in 
the southeast 
winter rapeseed is attractive as a rotation crop for winter 
grain and as an erosion control on idle land auld said thus 
commercial expansion of rapeseed in the southeast will hinge on the 
development of winter varieties that can be doublecropped 
dependably with soybeans 
the high plains and pacific northwest will see smaller increases 
in rapeseed production some loweryielding wheat in the plains 
probably will give way to rapeseed and in the northwest the crop 
could be rotated every fourth year with wheat 
field trials of early maturing hybrid winter rapeseed in the 
midwest have had mixed success and auld in the report predicted 
widespread commercial use of highyielding winter hybrids is not 
likely before 1995 
the report was written by margaret e thursland and jeanne f 
bailey of the usda agencys oilseeds and products division 
rapeseed is an ancient crop a member of the brassica family 
which includes mustard turnips and cabbage it is wellknown 
throughout asia middle east and europe as a vegetable oil and for 
industrial purposes 
canada is the leading exporter of rapeseed and japan is the no 
1 singlecountry importer canadas rapeseed exports to japan 
average about 15 million metric tons annually in 1989 us 
exports to japan were less than 2000 tons 
while the united states certainly cannot compete in volume 
with canadian producers there could be a niche as a residual 
supplier of rapeseed to japan and mexico the two largest importers 
of rapeseed outside of the european community the report said 
another factor in the future of us production is the easing of 
federal commodity programs to allow the substitution of certain 
crops including rapeseed and canola without losing crop acreage 
base 
