<TEXT>
consumer and business interest rates are 
unlikely to go lower in coming weeks despite political pressure on 
the federal reserve to abandon its tightmoney policy private 
economists say 
these analysts are forecasting that the prime lending rate 
offered by banks will stay at 10 percent where it has been since 
early january 
the prime rate is used by many banks as the benchmark in setting 
about half of their business and consumer loans including 
adjustablerate home equity loans 
mortgage rates which are currently averaging 1026 percent 
nationally for fixedrate loans will remain close to that level at 
least until fall when they might start falling slightly analysts 
say 
this forecast is based on an assumption that federal reserve 
officials who were in washington today to set monetary strategy 
will decide that inflationary risks make it unwise to reduce 
interest rates further 
the economy is growing although weakly while at the same 
time inflation is unacceptably high we have a tug of war between 
those two factors and that will produce no change by the central 
bank allen sinai chief economist of the boston co said monday 
david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a 
government securities dealer said that while there were 
indications that economic growth is rebounding and inflationary 
pressures are moderating it is too soon for the fed to know for 
sure that these favorable developments are occurring 
the fed is going to have to wait for at least a couple of 
months to get a true reading on where the economy is right now 
jones said for that reason i see no change coming out of this 
meeting 
federal reserve policymakers including board members in 
washington and presidents of fed regional banks meet eight times a 
year behind closed doors to review the economy and revise their 
interest rate targets 
private economists said they believed the central bank would 
stand firm against bush administration pressure to move quickly to 
reduce interest rates as a way of boosting economic growth 
the fed last eased credit conditions just before christmas and 
has resisted repeated urgings by the administration to make further 
changes 
a published report earlier this month quoted an unnamed 
presidential adviser as saying president bush was mad as hell 
and would not reappoint alan greenspan as chairman of the federal 
reserve board next year because of greenspans refusal to heed 
pleas for a looser credit policy 
as the year began many analysts were looking for quick action 
by the fed to lower interest rates in an effort to keep the country 
out of a recession given the fact that the economy in the final 
three months of 1989 had turned in its poorest performance in three 
years 
however business activity picked up early this year leading 
greenspan to say that he believed the danger point for a recession 
had passed 
also working against a looser credit policy is the fact that 
inflationary pressures increased significantly in recent months 
driven upward by cropkilling freezes and a spurt in energy costs 
in addition to domestic concerns over inflation and growth the 
fed is keeping an eye on international markets where the dollar 
has been climbing especially against the japanese yen 
the dollars strength so far this year concerns the 
administration and is one reason the white house has been 
pressuring the fed to lower interest rates 
lower us interest rates serve to push down the dollars value 
because they mean lower profits for foreign investors a lower 
dollar improves americas trade fortunes because it makes us 
goods more competitive on overseas markets and raises the cost of 
imports to american consumers 
david wyss chief economist of drimcgraw hill said that while 
he was not looking for any immediate action by the fed a small 
move toward lowering interest rates could occur later this spring 
if the central bank remains concerned about the dollars strength 
