<TEXT>
soviet soldiers on tuesday began 
rounding up lithuanians who fled the red army raiding hospitals 
where the men sought refuge after the republics declaration of 
independence from moscow 
witnesses said some of the young men were beaten as they were 
taken from a decaying psychiatric hospital in vilnius a trail of 
blood led down the steps and out the front door of the hospital 
it was the first reported violence in the confrontation between 
lithuania and the kremlin that began march 11 with the baltic 
republics attempt to withdraw from the union 
soviet troops also took over the communist party headquarters a 
showcase office building in the center of the lithuanian capital 
it was the fifth party building soviet forces had seized in recent 
days 
before dawn paratroopers took about two dozen men into custody 
at a psychiatric hospital in vilnius sharply escalating tensions 
that officials said monday seemed to be easing with the opening of 
talks between soviet military and republic officials 
a police officer in kaunas about 65 miles to the west said by 
telephone that soviet troops had taken control of the red cross 
hospital there which had served as a second sanctuary for 
deserters 
the police officer who did not identify himself said the 
soldiers were not allowing lithuanian police to enter the grounds 
of the hospital it was not immediately known if anyone was taken 
into custody there 
a lithuanian interior ministry official said a third hospital 
in a small town outside also was raided and that two or three 
former soldiers were taken away peacefully 
soviet military authorities had warned they would seize the men 
they considered deserters if the men did not return voluntarily by 
last saturday the lithuanian government contends the red army is 
an army of occupation 
lithuania was forcibly annexed by the soviet union in 1940 
along with the other two baltic republics of latvia and estonia 
independence movements have also sprung up in latvia estonia 
and other soviet republics posing one of the biggest challenges to 
president mikhail s gorbachev since he came to power in 1985 
the actions came after gorbachev told sen edward kennedy on 
monday that he would not use force in lithuania except to save 
lives 
in vilnius a nurse said about a dozen of the men who had been 
staying at the hospital escaped and that others were beaten by 
their captors 
they beat them with their fists a duty nurse said of the 
soviet soldiers who broke into the hospital about 3 am she 
refused to give her name i was afraid they would shoot me too 
the interior ministry official who did not give his name and a 
lithuanian journalist said two lithuanian policemen also were 
beaten by the soldiers when they sought to intervene to stop the 
violence 
a television crew from the american abc news network arrived at 
the scene while the troops were still there was held at gunpoint 
and forced to surrender its video tape 
they held us at gunpoint and told us not to move said 
andrzej lewandowski a member of the camera crew his colleague 
chris burzynski said the soldiers made them take all their 
equipment out of their car and seized all their video cassettes 
lithuanias president vytautas landsbergis suggested saturday 
that the deserters seek sanctuary in churches instead of the 
hospitals but few if any youths appeared to accept the proposal 
some lithuanian leaders said monday that talks that began the 
previous day with soviet military commanders had eased tensions in 
the breakaway republic but others were not so optimistic 
lithuanian deputy premier romualdas ozolas one of two officials 
who met two soviet military officers monday told reporters 
after coming out of this meeting i can say the mood has 
changed 
it is evident the conflict will not be escalated he said 
but president landsbergis was more skeptical he said he had not 
received clear assurances that no more buildings would be occupied 
moreover in a separate interview with the us national public 
radio landsbergis said the situation had become very dangerous 
in the light of gorbachevs remarks to kennedy 
before he always said that he would not use force in 
lithuania but now we have a situation where hes qualifying that 
statement and setting a condition under which he could use force 
soviet television said monday that soviet helicopters have been 
patrolling lithuanias borders daily because of reports 
territorial guard forces set up by the popular independence 
movement sajudis have been erecting border signs 
paratroopers appeared in vilnius on sunday at the higher party 
school and the institute of marxismleninism lithuanian officials 
said there also were soldiers at the vilnius communist party 
headquarters 
ozolas said that during the talks the army said it occupied the 
buildings at the request of lithuanian communists who remain loyal 
to moscow the majority of the party split with moscow in december 
reports in vilnius on monday night said paratroopers had 
occupied another building the communist party committees 
headquarters in the port of klaipeda 200 miles northwest of 
vilnius 
lithuanian journalist and activist vilus kavalauskas told 
reporters the paratroopers had arrived in response to a request by 
klaipedas assistant party chief kavalauskas did not say when the 
building was seized 
a helicopter dropped leaflets on vilnius urging people to attend 
an antiindependence rally tuesday outside parliament one set of 
leaflets was unsigned while another was signed by ussr citizens 
in lithuania the republic of 38 million has a large russian 
minority 
they are pushing the lithuanian people into an abyss of 
independence the leaflets warned think will we be free in 
this free state where the right to own property is given again 
into alien hands 
kennedy said gorbachev told him he was committed to solving the 
dispute with lithuania peacefully and only would use troops if 
lives were in danger 
speaking to a news conference after the meeting kennedy said 
the soviet leader indicated to me that the position of the soviet 
union was that there would be no use of force unless the lives of 
others were threatened and that he was committed to a peaceful 
resolution 
gorbachev did not say whether he thought any threat to human 
life was imminent in lithuania the massachusetts democrat reported 
at mondays talks in vilnius ozolas and lithuanian interior 
minister marijonas misiukonis met with col viktor smokarev deputy 
