<TEXT>
an overwhelming majority of the nations 
business leaders oppose a governmentrun national health plan 
according to a poll commissioned by the health insurance 
association of america 
the roper organization poll released monday found that 94 
percent of the business executives surveyed would reject a 
healthcare system with a budget controlled by the states or the 
federal government 
a majority of the executives 62 percent said they favored 
improving privatesector efforts to control healthcare costs and 
relying on the current level of government regulation while 31 
percent said they would favor more government regulation to control 
physician and hospital prices 
twothirds of the executives said that in the last year their 
corporate health care costs rose by 11 percent to 20 percent one 
in six said their costs were up 21 percent to 30 percent 
the poll also found that nine of 10 business leaders have made 
major changes in their health plans over the last two to three 
years to contain costs 
the most popular option chosen by threequarters of them was 
to shift more of the cost to employees by increasing deductibles 
and copayments and the workers share of premiums also 62 
percent said they have adopted managed care programs such as those 
based on health maintenance organizations and referred provider 
organizations 
