<TEXT>
couchbound bird watchers are entering 
a new television season watching their favorite stars two 
peregrine falcons in the permanent eye of a cable channels camera 
the camera mounted on the 21st story of a downtown office 
building clicked on again monday giving watchers a birds eye view 
of the falcons nest 
the falcons became tv stars last summer when the cable company 
mounted a camera near their nest on a ledge of the 23story monarch 
place office building the pictures were broadcast on a channel 
devoted to educational programming 
the show proved hugely popular with the cable outlets 43000 
subscribers and this year systems in westfield enfield longmeadow 
and northampton will also carry the falcons 
nobody else is using the public access channel so its entirely 
for the birds 
it amazes me that someone can sit and watch the birds hour 
after hour said brian lambert general manager of continental 
cablevision i am one of them it stays on in the office all day 
long we just kind of wait to see the bird move or the eggs or 
whatever its mesmerizing 
tom french director of the states endangered species program 
said the show is more than an entertaining glimpse of nature 
its an incredible opportunity he said its absolutely 
incredible that theyre so visible 
we often joke around the office that we spend tens and 
hundreds of thousands of dollars on new customer service features 
or new programming services and almost as a second thought we 
covered the peregrine falcons story and overnight it became an 
instant success lambert said 
running cable to the building and mounting the camera behind 
reflective glass cost about 10000 lambert said 
among the first season highlights were the first hatchings of 
young peregrine falcons in western massachusetts in 40 years and a 
june thriller when french rappelled down the side of the building 
to rescue a baby falcon that was choking on a piece of meat alert 
viewers had noticed the chicks distress and called in the 
situation to cable officials 
this season the first egg is expected to appear in early april 
the first hatching in midmay and the first fledgling flights near 
the end of june 
the show could have a long run because falcons mate for life 
and generally return to their nests year after year french said 
