rival centerright and liberal parties 
plotted strategies today to try to win enough support in runoff 
elections to form hungarys first postwar noncommunist government 
final results of the countrys first free elections in 43 years 
remained unavailable this afternoon two days after the last of 
millions of voters cast ballots for the 394seat parliament 
a final tally from the 11000 polls was not expected before late 
today and janos nemeth chairman of the national electoral 
committee blamed the interior ministry because its electoral 
office was supplying incomplete information on the voting to the 
committee 
nemeth did not specify whether he thought the interior ministry 
which many hungarians continue to associate with communist 
repression because of its control of internal security was 
willfully delaying results showing a poor performance by the 
oldguard communist party 
an interior ministry official who declined to give his name on 
the telephone denied the the delay was deliberate he said it was 
due to the slow transmission of data to the ministry from outlying 
polling stations 
more than 70 percent of hungarys 78 million eligible voters 
cast ballots election officials said by late monday only five of 
the seats were decided 
with more than 80 percent of the ballots cast for 29 parties 
running counted the conservative hungarian democratic forum led 
with 247 percent of the vote the centerleft league of free 
democrats had 216 percent and the ruralbased independent 
smallholders was in third with 119 percent 
the democratic forum wants to move more slowly than the free 
democrats toward marketoriented reform in grappling with an 
economy beset by doubledigit inflation and a 20 billion foreign 
debt after four decades of communist rule 
neither of the two leading parties garnered anything close to 
the absolute majority needed for decisive victory making a 
coalition government likely after runoff elections are held next 
month possibly on april 8 
democratic forum chairman joszef antall said the independent 
smallholders would be his first choice as coalition partners and 
like the free democrats he dismissed any idea of working with the 
socialists 
far back in fourth place with 107 percent were the ruling 
socialists the successors of the old communist party who 
campaigned on a democratic platform but apparently were still 
associated by voters with the communist past 
the apparent aversion to anything that smacked of socialism 
accounted for the poor showing by the social democrats who hadnt 
managed to clear the 4 percent hurdle needed to gain representation 
in parliament 
voters in east germany on march 18 had a similar reaction to 
four decades of communist rule choosing a conservative coalition 
the oldstyle communists who refused to join the reform wing in 
founding the socialist party last october also fared badly their 
leader gyula thuermer finished a distant fifth in a western 
district and the party also failed to clear the 4 percent hurdle 
preliminary results showed 
among the five seats decided outright were three taken by 
democratic forum members and one by premier miklos nemeth a reform 
communist the socialist party cofounder and chief supporter of 
democracy nemeth ran as an independent in his home riding of 
szerencs 70 miles northeast of budapest 
nemeth said his outgoing government should receive credit for 
leading the nation to sundays historic vote 
