<TEXT>
the supreme court today gave states new power 
to limit political campaign spending by corporations upholding a 
michigan law challenged by that states chamber of commerce 
voting 63 the justices said such restrictions are justified by 
the states interest in preventing corruption or even its 
appearance 
the court rejected arguments that the michigan law violates free 
speech rights of chamber of commerce members 
supporters of the state law said it is intended to prevent 
corporate giants such as the major automobile manufacturers from 
funneling millions of dollars through the chamber to favorite 
candidates without revealing the spending 
corporate wealth can unfairly influence elections when it is 
deployed in the form of independent expenditures justice 
thurgood marshall said for the court 
we therefore hold that the state has articulated a 
sufficiently compelling rationale to support its restriction on 
independent expenditures by corporations he said 
marshall also rejected arguments that the law is 
unconstitutional because it exempts labor unions and media 
corporations 
he noted that union members who disagree with a unions 
political activities can decline to contribute to them without 
giving up their membership 
media corporations merit exemption to protect the role of 
broadcasters and publishers in reporting and commenting on 
newsworthy events marshall added 
in a dissenting opinion justice antonin scalia said the 
court today endorses the principle that too much speech is an evil 
that the democratic majority can proscribe the principle is 
incompatible with the absolutely central truth of the first 
amendment that government cannot be trusted to assure through 
censorship the fairness of political debate 
justices anthony m kennedy and sandra day oconnor also 
dissented 
the ruling is a victory for the federal election commission 
which supported an appeal by michigan officials 
the michigan chamber of commerce has some 8000 duespaying 
members about threefourths of them corporations 
the chamber planned in 1985 to place a paid advertisement in the 
grand rapids press in support of richard bandstra a republican 
candidate for the state house of representatives 
fearing the ad would be considered illegal under michigans 
campaign finance act the business group filed a federal suit 
seeking to have the law declared unconstitutional as applied to the 
chamber 
the law generally prohibits corporations from spending in behalf 
of political candidates and carries a maximum 10000 fine 
the act permits a corporation to make such expenditures if it 
sets up a special fund or political action committee that is 
required to keep records and disclose the name of contributors 
the chamber has such a fund but it wanted to pay for the 
newspaper ad for bandstra out of its general treasury which is 
exempt from the recordkeeping and reporting requirements of the 
campaign finance law 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals exempted the chamber of 
commerce from the law 
the appeals court relied heavily on a 1986 supreme court ruling 
limiting the federal governments power to regulate corporate 
political spending 
the justices said then that the federal election campaign act of 
1971 violates freedom of speech when applied to corporations formed 
primarily to influence public opinion and not to make a profit 
the high court in 1986 ruled in favor of a massachusetts 
prolife group formed to protest the legalization of abortion 
but today the justices drew key distinctions between the 
massachusetts group and the chamber of commerce 
marshall said the prolife organizations narrow focus ensured 
its resources reflected political support for that issue the 
chambers more varied bylaws contain no such assurances he said 
moreover he said chamber members may be reluctant for economic 
reasons to withdraw from the organization even if they disagree 
with its political views 
the case is austin vs michigan chamber of commerce 881569 
</TEXT>
