<TEXT>
about half a billion people worldwide are 
suffering from tropical diseases such as malaria river blindness 
and sleeping sickness the world health organization said wednesday 
as it launched a campaign to fight the illnesses 
who officials appealed for more funds to pay for research and 
control programs for the great neglected diseases it said they 
pose a risk of infection to the entire population of the african 
continent and much of asia and south america 
the un agencys new campaign will focus attention on the seven 
most widespread tropical diseases which can cause internal organ 
damage limb deformities blindness brain damage and death 
dr shaik khader noordeen a senior official in whos tropical 
diseases division told a news conference that lack of money 
prevented effective use of preventive measures and drugs to counter 
the diseases 
a lot can be done today but it is not being done simply 
because the resources are not available in the endemic countries 
and the awareness is not present in the countries that could help 
them he said 
dr alvaro moncayo another who expert said the organizations 
current research budget into tropical diseases was 6570 million 
spread over a twoyear period 
whos 1990 budget for its program on aids totals 109 million 
these diseases affect the poorest of the poor moncaya said 
when asked why he thought tropical diseases had not received the 
same attention as aids 
a who report said most victims of tropical diseases live in 
countries with average per capita incomes of less than 400 and 
where governments spend a yearly average of just 4 per person on 
health care 
the 26page report said malaria claimed the highest number of 
victims it estimated that 270 million people carry the parasite 
spread by infected mosquitos with 110 million new cases each year 
it put the annual number of fatalities at 1 million to 2 million 
the report said 21 billion people live in areas of the third 
world where they are at risk the parasite is showing increasing 
resistance to common drugs it said 
schistosomiasis a disease caused by waterborne parasites from 
snails afflicted about 200 million people destroying internal 
tissues and contributing to malnutrition according to the report 
more than 110 million people suffer from filariasis caused by 
mosquitos and blackflies it leads to river blindness or 
onchocerciasis a disease transmitted by flies that causes tumors 
skin lesions and blindness filariasis may also lead to a painful 
swelling of the limbs known as elephantiasis it said 
who also singled out for concern chagas disease found in 
central and south america and occasionally in the united states it 
said there were 1618 million cases of the disease caused by a 
parasite transmitted by a bloodsucking bug that lives in crevices 
of poorquality houses 
in later stages of the disease the parasites invade body organs 
and eventually cause irreversible damage to the heart and 
intestines the disease is said to be incurable but can be 
prevented by insecticides better housing and health education 
a fifth disease sleeping sickness is transmitted by the bite 
of the tsetse fly in several parts of africa the report said early 
diagnosis was difficult and for the 25000 people who contract the 
disease each year it was invariably fatal 
it said insecticide spraying and tsetse traps had proved 
successful as preventive measures 
it estimated that 12 million people were infected with 
leishmaniasis caused by a sandfly bite some 400000 new cases 
occur each year with victims suffering ailments ranging from 
ulcers to chronic tissue destruction 
in a glimmer of hope in the otherwise gloomy report who said 
leprosy had recently become controllable by treatment involving 
three drugs by the end of last year 175 million of the 4 million 
registered patients had received the therapy 
who estimates there are 1012 million cases of leprosy worldwide 
</TEXT>
