<TEXT>
lithuanian president vytautas 
landsbergis today accused moscow of inexcusable aggression and 
demanded that it return at least 23 lithuanian army deserters who 
were beaten and dragged from hospitals 
the government of lithuania demands the return of its 
kidnapped citizens landsbergis said in a letter to soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev he also urged negotiations with 
moscow in neutral territory 
the letters angry tone and the soviet armys decision to round 
up the deserters marked a new more volatile stage in the open 
confrontation between lithuania and moscow which began march 11 
with the republics declaration of independence the beatings 
reported during the roundup of lithuanian deserters were the first 
violent action by moscow since the declaration 
soviet soldiers raided two hospitals where the lithuanian 
deserters had sought refuge and witnesses said some deserters were 
beaten as they were taken from a decaying psychiatric hospital in 
vilnius a trail of blood led down the steps and out the front door 
of the hospital 
they beat them with their fists said a duty nurse at a 
psychiatric hospital where windows and iron beds were broken in the 
predawn raid 
landsbergis said he feared it could presage a fullscale 
crackdown on his baltic republic 
it is obvious that the soviet armed forces have been given 
permission to use violence landsbergis said 
the soviet union today also ordered all foreigners to leave 
lithuania foreign ministry spokesman yuri gremitskikh said in 
moscow last week diplomats and foreign journalists were told they 
could not travel to the republic 
in washington white house spokesman marlin fitzwater refused to 
criticize moscow for todays actions saying we do not want to 
