<TEXT>
a government commission on tuesday said racism 
particularly against north african immigrants is spreading in 
france and premier michel rocard asked all political parties to 
combat this threat to our national heritage 
rocard made his appeal after receiving a 400page report from a 
commission appointed to investigate what has become the countrys 
most pressing social problem 
racial tensions intensified during the sixmonth investigation 
this month alone three moroccan immigrants have been killed in 
incidents that prompted protests by human rights groups 
the socialist government and its centerright rivals have called 
for tolerance but the farright national front has stepped up its 
campaign against immigration 
the commission said racism against north africans was the most 
widespread increasing markedly in 1989 about 4 million of 
frances 55 million residents are immigrants mainly moslems from 
north africa 
the commission said 75 percent of french people responding to a 
survey it conducted said they believe there are too many north 
africans in france 
the report said the number of racial attacks and threats jumped 
to 237 in november and december compared to 135 in the same period 
of 1988 the increase followed a nationwide controversy that 
focused on whether moslem girls should be allowed to wear islamic 
scarves to public schools 
the controversy focused attention on immigrants place in french 
society the nationwide debate began when several local school 
officials barred moslem girls from classes because they insisted on 
wearing traditional islamic scarves the officials cited a law 
prohibiting display of religious symbols in schools 
the government eventually relented saying the scarves could be 
worn as long as education was not disrupted 
antisemitism also persists the commission said referring to 
revisionist theories that the nazi concentration camps did not 
exist it cited skinhead and facist groups as among the 
culprits 
racism is found at all levels of social life and in all parts 
of the country said the commission which decried the 
exploitation of racial fears by political candidates 
in incidents this month a bus driver was charged with willful 
homicide for running over and killing a 17yearold immigrant a 
cook shot at two moroccan brothers killing one and a police 
brigadier was detained briefly after shooting to death a young 
moroccan who purportedly tried to escape from a police vehicle 
after being arrested 
the report said political and civic leaders need a twopronged 
approach the will to enforce laws against racism and the foresight 
to take preventative steps 
these priorities should be coupled with efforts to enhance the 
assimilation of immigrants into french society and eliminate 
discrimination it said 
rocard invited leaders of his own socialist party the two 
centerright parties and the communist party to a meeting april 3 
to launch an antiracism initiative no invitation was sent to the 
national front whose leader jean marie le pen has described the 
political hierarchys outcry over racism as indecent 
the recent violence according to le pen is directly tied to 
social phenomena resulting from immigration policies which they are 
directly responsible for 
