<TEXT>
foreigners are not always required to disclose 
the millions of dollars they pay american lobbyists to promote 
their point of view witnesses told congress tuesday 
sen john heinz rpenn said he has proposed legislation to 
strengthen the foreign agents registration act so foreigners will 
not be able to subvert us policy and national security 
he singled out the japanese as among the biggest spenders 
between 1987 and 1989 the total spent by all registered agents for 
japanese entities was more than 120 million heinz estimated 
the act first passed in 1938 requires lobbyists to disclose 
the amount of money they receive from foreign governments and what 
they do for the fee but it is fraught with loopholes witnesses 
said 
another witness before the senate foreign relations committee 
owen bieber said reforms are needed bieber is president of the 
international union united automobile aerospace and agricultural 
implement workers of america 
foreign governments and companies today are spending hundreds 
of millions of dollars to influence public policy in our country 
he said the sheer amount of money and the manner in which it is 
spent are distorting our political process these excesses demand 
reform 
heinz said his interest was piqued recently by a case involving 
toshiba corps efforts to avoid congressional sanctions after 
toshiba machine sold the soviet union precision milling equipment 
used for the production of submarine propellers 
toshiba paid the law firm of mudge rose guthrie alexander and 
ferndon nearly 11 million to act on its behalf heinz said but 
heinz said toshibas scores of subsidiaries were not required to 
register 
registration is not presently required for most subsidiaries 
or for clients where the agent did not engage in any reportable 
activity heinz said 
heinz bill would make three principal changes 
it would force companies that are more than 50 percent foreign 
owned to register with the justice department when they hire 
lobbyists 
it would repeal an exemption now granted to lawyers for 
administrative or judicial proceedings 
it would require all agents to file their forms on jan 30 and 
june 30 instead of every six months from the day they registered 
bieber praised the legislation but suggested it could go 
further for one thing congress should act to end the revolving 
door between us trade officials and foreign companies 
starting on jan 1 1991 former federal officials who have been 
involved in trade or treaty negotiations will be prohibited from 
aiding or assisting any foreign company or government with which 
they had negotiated the ban will be in effect for a year 
bieber also said i believe the time has come to start looking 
at imposing limits on the amounts that foreign governments and 
companies can spend to lobby our legislative and executive branches 
of government 
sen claiborne pell dri the committee chairman agreed with 
heinz that the act will have to be tightened up steadily as we go 
along 
