<TEXT>
the pentagon defended the administrations 
policy of maintaining a chemical weapons stockpile on tuesday as a 
spokesman confirmed it is considering forcing two chemical firms to 
sell the army a key ingredient for poison gas 
the army has used up its supplies of the chemical thionyl 
chloride accrued from the 1950s and has sought new supplies from 
occidental petroleum co and the pittsburghbased mobay corp a 
subsidiary of the west german chemical firm bayer ag officials 
said 
both companies have refused to supply the chemical and told the 
pentagon their corporate policies bar them from providing chemicals 
that would be used in the production of chemical weapons 
given the firms responses officials from the two agencies are 
conferring on what action to take 
the administration could invoke the defense production act of 
1950 which gives the government the authority to compel the sale 
of material to the pentagon for reasons of national security 
in the meantime the army is attempting to locate thionyl 
chloride from other sources pentagon spokesman bob hall told 
reporters at a briefing 
the chemical is used to make the poison gas to fill the 
artillery shells for binary chemical weapons that could be used in 
battle 
president bush has decried the proliferation of chemical weapons 
and the administration has proposed a treaty limiting their use 
but pending an international accord the administration contends 
the united states must maintain a supply of such weapons to deter 
their use by other nations 
the administration also has attempted to block the export of the 
chemical to nations believed to be involved in chemical weapons 
production 
hall noted that the next step could be up to the department of 
commerce which as yet has not directed the companies to provide 
the chemical to the us government 
they have the authority under the defense production act of 
1950 to compel acceptance of defenserelated production orders 
by companies capable of producing the required item or material 
hall said 
he noted that as the administration has moved ahead with its 
plans to destroy its old stockpiles of unitary chemical weapons 
those that carry a lethal gas mixture it decided to move ahead 
with production of binary weapons which use two chemicals that mix 
and become lethal only after being fired 
as we destroy the unitary weapons stockpiles we are producing 
a small stockpile of binary chemical weapons which will serve as a 
deterrence against the use of chemical weapons against the united 
states hall said 
there are good reasons why we want to maintain a reserve 
stockpile during the process of negotiating the treaty and 
particularly the binary because they are a better system hall 
said we need to proceed with this small program to do so we 
need the chemicals supplied by commercial suppliers 
hall said there are other companies that could be potential 
sources of the chemical but he declined to identify them or state 
whether they were able to supply the material 
