<TEXT>
brazils two stock markets 
continued to plunge monday in the aftermath of draconian economic 
reforms decreed by new president fernando collor de mello 
in rio the stock market was off by a record 162 percent and 
has now fallen by onethird since collor announced his package mar 
16 
the muchlarger sao paulo exchange dropped by 6 percent monday 
after plunging 49 percent last week 
stock market analysts say the fall on the two exchanges is 
largely due to a lack of money in circulation 
collors economic package designed to cut record inflation of 
73 percent in february included an 18month freeze on assets of 
more than 1200 in private bank savings accounts and 600 on 
shortterm money market deposits the measure took about 115 
billion out of circulation 80 percent of all bank deposits 
stock investors desperate to get their hands on cash are 
selling off shares even at low prices analysts say 
the money squeeze has also created a steep drop in business 
sales and large scale layoffs in some industries with many 
economists saying brazil latin americas most populous with 150 
million residents could soon be mired in a deep recession 
</TEXT>
