the national science foundation on tuesday 
announced up to 10 million will be provided to selected states 
with detailed plans to stimulate major improvements in math and 
science education 
foundation director erich bloch said the new science education 
improvement effort supports the goal of president bush and the 
nations governors to make american students first in the world in 
science and mathematics achievement by the year 2000 
to prosper in this world the united states must maintain a 
strong base in science and engineering because that is the basis 
for much of our economic strength said bloch who stressed the 
need for systemic changes in state education programs 
bloch said that the foundation expects in the first year to 
select four to eight states on a competitive basis to participate 
in the program 
we will look for comprehensive plans to improve statewide 
science and mathematics education significantly not simply to 
tinker with the details he said plans will need to deal with 
teacher preparation retention and continuing education with 
curriculum improvements with student motivation and with 
upgrading educational facilities 
bloch said the plans also must include governors state 
legislative leaders chief state school officers teachers 
organizations school administrators unions and parent groups 
industry leaders and presidents of colleges and universities 
noting the numerous studies documenting the poor achievements of 
us students in math and science bloch said we want to move 
beyond studies and beyond planning in the abstract to real 
action 
for the selected states the foundation will make grants 
totaling 5 million to 10 million over the expected life of the 
project bloch said that significant systemic changes must be 
supported through longterm fiscal commitments from state 
legislatures and other sources public and private to assure 
permanence of the reforms begun in the program 
bloch said states must submit preliminary proposals for the 
statewide initiatives program by july 9 with the deadline for 
formal proposals set for oct 15 
