<TEXT>
the nations top savings and loan official 
pleaded with congress on tuesday to give president bushs thrift 
bailout program a chance to work before changing or scrapping it 
what we need now is stability constant tinkering even with 
the best of intentions imposes tremendous costs on the industry 
the regulatory system and the american public said salvatore 
martoche acting director of the treasury departments office of 
thrift supervision 
rep frank annunzio dill and his house banking subcommittee 
on financial institutions are reviewing suggestions for changing 
the sampl law enacted nearly eight months ago tuesdays session was 
the third of five scheduled 
proposals range from abolishing the thrift office and dividing 
its duties among commercial bank regulators to providing temporary 
relief from lending rules that some home builders say are crimping 
their credit 
martoche conceded that some changes might improve the law but 
said the benefits were outweighed by the potential harm of 
disruptive changes 
ive been around legislative bodies long enough to know that 
when you do a reopener everything but the kitchen sink gets taken 
up he said 
the sampl law sharply reduced the maximum amount an institution 
can loan to one borrower the intent was to prevent the bankruptcy 
of a single customer from severely hurting a thrift however 
builders complain that they cant get the loans they need and say 
the limit should be phased in gradually 
martoche said the thrift office is leaning toward phasing in the 
restrictions over two years but is uncertain whether the law will 
permit that the agency has given industry lawyers 60 days to 
suggest a creative solution to the dilemma he said 
on another matter martoche said he was not concerned about the 
agencys slow pace in reviewing financial plans submitted by ailing 
thrifts by jan 7 the sampl law required weak institutions to get 
goverment approval for their plans to raise capital 
so far 577 sampls have submitted plans the thrift office has 
rejected 127 approved 64 and told many institutions to go back 
to the drawing board martoche said later tuesday the agency 
announced it was extending its deadline for approving the plans 
from the end of march to the end of april 
i cant help but feel that some institutions were testing us 
to see if lax plans would be approved he said i want them 
agency employees to do the right thing and however long it takes 
it takes 
martoche who is an assistant treasury secretary began the 
thrift job on an acting basis only three weeks ago after m danny 
wall left the position under fire he is already a lame duck 
in response to lawsuits from weak sampls challenging the 
constitutional authority of both wall and martoche president bush 
last week nominated t timothy ryan jr to a fiveyear term as the 
permanent director of the thrift office 
the senate banking committee has scheduled a confirmation 
hearing on wednesday for ryan formerly the top lawyer at the labor 
department from 1981 to 1983 
in another development the federal deposit insurance corp 
approved a controversial plan to pump money into ailing sampls before 
they fail to qualify institutions must be in one of eight 
economically troubled states managers must be subject to firing 
shareholders must be treated approximately as if the sampl had 
failed and new private investment must be injected into the sampl 
along with the government funds 
however it remains unclear if the policy will ever be used 
another agency the treasury departmentled resolution trust corp 
oversight board has expressed reservations the board would have to 
approve any spending for thrift assistance 
i hate the notion of giving shareholders who were responsible 
for running an institution down the tubes any benefit of a 
bailout martoche said i personally find that abhorrent 
several members of the house banking panel also opposed the 
policy including rep bruce vento dminn chairman of a task 
force overseeing the bailout 
fdic chairman l william seidman however says open thrift 
assistance can be cheaper for taxpayers in some cases 
institutions in eight states will be eligible alaska arizona 
arkansas colorado louisiana new mexico oklahoma and texas 
