<TEXT>
six centerright and liberal parties 
advanced to the second round of campaigning tuesday to try to win 
enough support in runoff elections to form hungarys first 
postwar noncommunist government 
janos nemeth chairman of the national electoral committee said 
the final tally in sundays parliamentary elections was delayed 
because the interior ministrys electoral office had given the 
committee incomplete information 
nemeth did not specify whether he thought the interior ministry 
which many hungarians still associate with communist repression 
because of its control of internal security was purposely delaying 
results showing a poor performance by old guard communists 
they refused to join communist reformers in founding the 
socialist party in october and failed to win 4 percent of the 
national vote necessary to gain representation in parliament 
a ministry official who declined to give his name on the 
telephone said the delay in reporting results was due to slow 
transmission of votes from outlying polling stations 
the electoral committee announced unofficial final results but 
said the elections would have to be repeated in five districts 
where fewer than half the eligible voters turned out the state 
news agency mti reported 
the conservative hungarian democratic forum received 247 
percent of the vote to maintain its edge over the centerleft 
league of free democrats who won 214 percent 
the ruralbased independent smallholders finished third with 
117 percent followed by the socialists the successors to 
hungarys communist party with 109 percent 
the league of young democrats won 89 percent and the christian 
democratic peoples party 64 percent 
the rest of the 29 parties that ran did not clear the 4 percent 
hurdle 
more than 70 percent of hungarys 78 million eligible voters 
cast ballots election officials said 
only five of the parliaments 394 seats were decided 
since neither of the two leading parties garnered anything close 
to the absolute majority needed for decisive victory a coalition 
government is likely after runoff elections are held next month 
possibly april 8 
the biggest issue is hungarys economy which is beset by 
doubledigit inflation and a 20 billion foreign debt after four 
decades of communist rule 
the democratic forum and the free democrats both want to move 
toward marketoriented reforms but the forum wants to move more 
slowly 
both parties have said they do not want to join with the other 
in building a coalition government and the independent 
smallholders are expected to play a key role in such a government 
