the house overwhelmingly passed legislation 
tuesday to prevent trucks used to ship food from hauling garbage on 
the return trip 
the legislation which is opposed by the bush administration 
would also require that asbestos infectious waste and other 
healththreatening items be shipped only in vehicles designated for 
that purpose 
the vote was 41015 to send the proposal to the senate where 
similar bills are pending 
the bills prime target is backhauling the practice of 
using trucks that carry food crosscountry to carry municipal 
garbage on the trip home 
backhauling is dangerous disgusting and legal rep william 
clinger rpa one of the measures prime sponsors said during 
the brief floor debate on the legislation 
concern about foodgarbage hauls arose after the centre daily 
times of state college pa reported a year ago that refrigerated 
foodhauling trucks known as reefers were being loaded with 
municipal solid waste 
the report led congress to investigate a related practice 
alternating loads of chemicals with shipments of juice or edible 
oils an oregon truckers shipment log released by a house panel at 
an october hearing included loads of cooking oil wine apple 
juice fire retardant marine lubricant and lime sulphur 
several trucking groups have said that concern by food companies 
has led many truckers to avoid the practice but clinger and rep 
chris smith rnj said checks by their staffs have confirmed 
that backhauling is continuing 
the government says it has not uncovered any instances of 
contamination due to backhauling 
the bush administration has opposed the backhauling ban largely 
because of a provision that the department of transportation would 
assume enforcement responsibility 
alan i roberts a hazardous materials specialist with the 
department told a senate panel three weeks ago that existing law 
is adequate to regulate the handling and transportation of food 
if a bill were approved he said lead responsibility should more 
properly rest with the agencies that have foodsafety expertise 
the agriculture department and the food and drug administration 
the administration has yet to see fit to correct these 
practices said rep tom luken dohio evidently the 
department of transportation thinks it is the problem of the food 
and drug administration the fda thinks its a transportation 
problem and the epa which has jurisdiction over solid waste 
doesnt know what to think 
voting against the bill were reps bill archer rtexas dick 
armey rtexas dan burton rind larry combest rtexas philip 
