<TEXT>
a jury was sworn in tuesday in the federal fraud 
and racketeering trial of imelda marcos and the judge said opening 
arguments would begin next week 
earlier us district judge john f keenan ruled that bank 
records from the philippines hong kong and singapore could be used 
as evidence in the trial of the former philippines first lady and 
saudi financier adnan khashoggi 
selection of the jury and six alternates was completed near the 
end of the trials first day keenan asked jurors to return to 
court next tuesday when the trial is to resume with opening 
arguments 
the panel consists of three postal workers two transit and two 
utility employees a retired secretary a teachers aide an 
engineer a computer operator and an estate manager with a law firm 
mrs marcos attorneys had sought to block the bank documents 
but the judge decided they were admissible because prosecutors had 
filed the proper certification 
the judge reserved a ruling on the admissibility of documents 
from italy switzerland and west germany saying he would rule 
before the start of the trials opening arguments possibly next 
week 
among documents allowed as evidence were 2000 pages of records 
from two trust accounts at the standard chartered bank of hong 
kong which prosecutors alleged were controlled by mrs marcos and 
her husband ferdinand who died in exile in hawaii on sept 28 
keenan said the government will use the trust account records to 
try to establish that the marcoses owned three panamanian companies 
that in turn owned a building at 40 wall st in new york 
the building is among four manhattan properties that prosecutors 
claim the marcoses bought with more than 160 million they stole 
from the philippines treasury 
the singapore bank records relate to the alleged transfer of 
millions of dollars for the purchase of 40 wall st the judge 
said the other records found admissible were from the traders 
royal bank in manila 
mrs marcos 60 is charged with racketeering racketeering 
conspiracy mail fraud and obstruction of justice if convicted 
she faces up to 50 years in prison and a 1 million fine 
khashoggi is accused of helping the marcoses conceal the real 
estate deals he faces up to 10 years in prison and 500000 in 
fines if convicted of mail fraud and obstruction of justice 
marcos the former philippines president had been named in the 
original october 1988 indictment the trial is expected to last 
three to four months 
