<TEXT>
senior un officials said tuesday 
that the millions of afghan refugees in pakistan and iran should 
return home and begin rebuilding their wartorn nation 
it is clear that somehow weve got to help feed them in 1990 
but this cant go on forever world food program executive 
director james ingram told reporters 
sadruddin aga khan the un coordinator for humanitarian aid 
and thorvald stoltenberg the un high commissioner for refugees 
also attended the news conference 
ingram said the afghan civil war between the marxist government 
and moslem guerrillas has lasted for 10 or 11 years already and 
now there is an opportunity to make progress in the return of 
refugees 
about 38 million afghans live in a maze of refugee camps 
scattered along pakistans border another 2 million live in iran 
while insisting the refugees must go home voluntary sadruddin 
said the united nations hoped that rebuilding their destroyed 
country might be the catalyst to spark their return 
most of the refugees fled after soviet soldiers marched into 
afghanistan in 1979 to replace one communist government with 
another and to crush the moslem insurgency 
moscow withdrew the last of its troops in february 1989 but 
most refugees have stayed in pakistan while the war continues 
between the usbacked guerrillas and the sovietsupported 
government in kabul 
sadruddin has made fresh appeals for contributions toward his 
12 billion repatriation plan the money is to be used to rebuild 
afghanistan where the war has ruined the economy wiped out herds 
and farmlands and destroyed thousands of villages 
sadruddin has suggested the refugees return to parts of 
afghanistan where there has been little or no fighting in recent 
months these areas would be designated peace zones 
he said renewed fighting instigated by either the kabul 
government or the guerrillas would end un assistance 
the price to pay will be no un aid said sadruddin 
who returned tuesday from a daylong trip to kabul 
however afghan and western sources fear another round of 
fighting will begin once the snow melts and weapons can be ferried 
from pakistan across the rugged mountain passes to afghan cities 
