<TEXT>
the sandinista government and 
negotiators for presidentelect violeta barrios de chamorro reached 
a preliminary agreement tuesday for a transfer of power on april 25 
the procedural protocol calls demobilization of the 
usbacked contra rebels an essential element for handing over 
the government 
it says the new government will have control of the leftist 
sandinista army and police and that only these institutions should 
have combat weapons 
the document also says the conservative chamorro government will 
respect the rights of thousands of people given confiscated land 
and homes during a decade of revolutionary sandinista rule 
the sandinistas have been handing out thousand of weapons to 
civilians since their feb 25 election defeat and have been urging 
people to defend the conquests of the revolution 
they also have indicated an unwillingness to turn over control 
of the armed forces and police as long as the contras remain an 
armed force 
the protocol says the army and the police will be nonpartisan 
organizations 
the accord was announced late tuesday by the leaders of the 
transition teams defense minister gen humberto ortega of the 
sandinistas and antonio lacayo of mrs chamorros united national 
opposition coalition or uno 
lacayo said the agreement envisions the demobilization of the 
contras by the time mrs chamorro takes office april 25 as called 
for in an agreement reached friday in honduras between uno and the 
rebels 
helicopters of a un observer force meanwhile began flying over 
nicaraguan war zones tuesday in preparation for the contra 
demobilization 
twelve white helicopters emblazoned with the un symbol landed 
at sandinista army installations tuesday morning and two hours 
later took off to the east 
military sources said the aircraft carried members of the 
observer force to eastern jungle zones where they will try to 
contact contra chiefs 
under an agreement reached friday rebels in honduran base camps 
are to disband and return to nicaragua by april 20 rebels in 
nicaragua are to move into security zones under the supervision of 
the un force and cardinal miguel obando y bravo 
the state department on monday said the force should be 
increased from the 200member level agreed to last year by five 
central american presidents that agreement was when its task was 
only to monitor the nicaraguanhonduran border 
the un security council on tuesday approved adding another 800 
troops to the force 
it was not known how many members of the force were in nicaragua 
on tuesday 
fighting has intensified since the signing of the accord friday 
according to the government a contra leader on monday denied the 
reports of combat 
the government proposed that the security zones in which rebels 
are to be moved before they demobilize be small it also said the 
zones should not be in remote regions and that there should not be 
many of them the newspaper barricada said 
it said the assistant defense minister maj gen joaquin cuadra 
lacayo made the suggestions to gen agustin quesada gomez of 
spain chief of the un force 
quesada gomez arrived monday after being called urgently by the 
sandinista government and was expected to travel to honduras to 
show the government proposals to the contras there on wednesday 
rebel commander oscar sovalbarro said the contras are willing to 
move to security zones but only temporarily until the 
demobilization and disarmament process is completed 
international observers and reporters said this week the rebel 
camps in honduras are nearly vacant indicating most of the 
estimated 12000 fighters have infiltrated back into nicaragua 
sovalbarro the contra negotiator in the accord said monday 
that 2000 rebel fighters had returned since friday they joined an 
estimated 4000 who were believed to have returned between 
september and the feb 25 election 
according to barricada the sandinistas proposed that the zones 
have the infrastructure to make them easily accessible for the un 
force and the cardinal 
although the agreement specifies no date for completion of the 
demobilization of forces in nicaragua cuadra insisted it be 
simultaneous with the dismantling in honduras 
