<TEXT>
the us department of energy should have 
known that hydrogen gas building up in nuclear waste storage tanks 
was potentially explosive a former nuclear regulatory commission 
worker said tuesday 
energy department officials said at a meeting with state 
regulators that they became aware only in the past two months of 
the explosion potential at the hanford nuclear reservation 
however they said they were aware as early as 1977 there was 
gas in the huge tanks because the waste level was rising 
in the late 70s and early 80s you first saw a rise and you 
knew nitrous oxide and hydrogen were in there and there was no 
question of flammability said bob cook a former nrc 
representative at hanford and now member of a citizens panel 
looking into the explosive tank issue 
its incredible for me to believe when there is a 22 percent 
hydrogen gas volume in the experiments and that was not considered 
an explosive mixture he said 
energy department officials said they unsuccessfully began 
trying to remove the gas in 1984 
don wodrich a westinghouse hanford co scientist studying the 
tanks said past concerns and action focused only on hydrogen in 
air spaces between the waste level and the roof of the tanks and 
not on hydrogen trapped in air bubbles within the waste itself 
the combination of hydrogen with nitrous oxide and other 
decomposing organics trapped under the hard crust formed at the top 
of the wastes created the new explosion threat he said that was 
discovered only in late february wodrich said 
state regulators said they were satisfied with the steps doe had 
taken to solve the problem so far and agreed that the risk of 
explosion appeared low 
but even a low risk is an unacceptable risk said al conklin 
of the state office of radiation protection 
i dont think people should start running away from hanford 
the problem is not that serious conklin said but i will not 
tell people we dont have a hazard 
the issue became public last friday when hanford manager mike 
lawrence announced that new findings indicated that hydrogen was 
building up inside up to 20 of hanfords 169 storage tanks he said 
there was a low risk of the hydrogen catching fire or exploding 
