<TEXT>
the lutherans want philip morris to get out of 
the tobacco business 
minnesotas state employees want texaco to pledge not to 
discriminate against roman catholics in northern ireland animal 
rights groups want better living conditions for the chickens 
purchased by kentucky fried chicken 
these and scores of other organizations are using investments in 
us corporations to pressure their companies to adopt their 
positions on political and social issues 
this year the hot issue is the environment with the 
shareholders of more than 30 companies proposing that they be 
allowed to vote on issues ranging from putting environmentalists on 
corporate boards to redesigning exxons tanker fleet 
when exxon holds its annual meeting april 25 and when exxon 
shareholders get proxy ballots in the mail no fewer than eight 
environmental proposals will be raised by stockholders 
but environmental issues are by no means the only ones being 
raised from within corporate america 
the conservative caucus for example wants chevron to refuse to 
deal with governments that vote more than 80 percent of the time 
against the us position at the united nations 
the united methodist church and other denominations working 
through the interfaith center on corporate responsibility want 
bristolmyers squibb to stop advertising infant formula on 
television 
the society for the prevention of cruelty to animals wants 
pepsico to investigate living conditions of the chickens it buys 
for its subsidiary kentucky fried chicken 
what these stockholder activists are practicing is called 
corporate democracy 
in fact some of these investors own stocks for the sole purpose 
of influencing a companys course theye out to make a point not 
a profit 
corporate democracy got its start in 1932 when lewis gilbert 
then a young newspaperman was gaveled to silence when he tried to 
ask some questions at the annual meeting of consolidated gas co 
in which he owned 10 shares 
gilbert stormed out quit his job and has devoted his life to 
fighting this silent dictatorship over other peoples money 
ever since he and his brother john have attended as many as 100 
annual meetings a year to demand that management heed stockholders 
most corporations hold their annual meetings in the spring so 
many a chief executive officer is preparing for a day of frayed 
nerves 
not that the stockholder proponents will win they hardly ever 
do last year about 500 stockholder proposals were advanced 170 
of them reached a vote but only five got a majority 
in any case the proposals are only advisory they dont compel 
management to do anything although management often gets the 
message and often negotiates to meet the stockholders demands 
even before the issue reaches a vote 
it used to be commonplace for stockholder proposals to get under 
3 percent of the vote or less 
but these days we often get 10 to 25 percent and it sends a 
strong message when management knows that such a critical mass of 
their shareholders want them to leave south africa or improve their 
environmental records says timothy smith who runs the 
interfaith center on corporate responsibility 
smiths group coordinates the investments of 240 roman catholic 
and protestant church groups with assets of 25 billion this 
spring the churches are bringing proposals before the stockholders 
of more than 150 companies 
asked why corporations negotiate when theyre sure of beating 
down stockholder proposals smith said one chief executive 
officer told us it is not in the best interests of our company to 
be seen doing battle with the christian church on an important 
ethcial issue 
so proponents claim some impressive victories even though they 
technically lost 
a number of us companies have cut ties with south africa 
stockholder activists say they are due some of the credit for 
cracks in the walls of apartheid 
keeping the pressure on institutions with assets of over 250 
billion have filed proposals this year that call on additional 
companies to sever south african ties 
in the 1970s and 1980s more than 100 planned nuclear plants 
were canceled in part from pressure by antinuclear stockholder 
groups 
keeping track of corporate democracy whos proposing what to 
whom is the business of the investor responsibility research 
center a nonprofit washington outfit that owes its existence to a 
black student protest at harvard university in 1972 
the students had taken over a campus building to demand that the 
university sell its gulf oil stock on the grounds that gulf was 
supporting angolas status as the black colony of a white nation 
portugal 
harvard president derek bok had difficulty finding the facts of 
the case the university said that if it simply sold its gulf stock 
it would forfeit any power it has to influence gulfs policies 
that episode led to the decision by some of the biggest names in 
philanthrophy the ford rockefeller and carnegie foundations all 
with heavy portfolios to create irrc they gave it the mission of 
assembling impartial information about corporate behavior and 
stockholder proposals 
i think corporations behave somewhat differently knowing that 
more and more and bigger and bigger shareholders are looking over 
their shoulders says executive director margaret carroll who 
has been with the center from the start 
part of irrcs mission is informing institutional investors of 
the proposals raised by activists 
pension funds banks insurance companies mutual funds college 
endowment funds foundations and other vast pools of money account 
for 75 percent of the trading at the new york stock exchange they 
have a fiduciary responsibility to know what they are voting on 
about 350 institutions from the bank of america to the 
archdiocese of new york pay irrc from 800 to 22000 a year to 
keep track of 1500 corporations 
the center gathers data from the corporations themselves the 
securities and exchange commission newspaper clippings and the 
fine print on the ballots known as proxy statements that companies 
mail shareholders these tell what the proponents want to do and 
why the board of directors doesnt want to do it 
we find the materials they produce quite useful says jim 
heidelberg assistant to the executive director of the minnesota 
state board of investment which invests 126 billion in pension 
funds of minnesota state employees and retirees 
adds the interfaith centers timothy smith their research is 
exceptionally important it is used around the country by 
shareholders who attempt to act as socially responsible investors 
the minnesota legislature has passed laws prohibiting the 
investment of retirement funds in certain ways so in its role as 
an investor minnesota is asking fellow stockholders of such 
companies as texaco security pacific and sonoco to vote to request 
a report on corporate attempts to combat anticatholic bias in 
their facilities in northern ireland other states do the same 
under sec regulations corporations may deny a place on the 
proxy ballot for proposals that deal with ordinary business 
operations on those grounds tobacco companies were able to beat 
back proposals dealing with tobacco sales 
but this year the sec staff reversed itself and allowed a 
tobacco question to go before stockholders so shareholders of 
philip morris and two other tobacco companies will vote on whether 
their companies should get out of the tobacco business by dec 31 
1999 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

