<TEXT>
 
blue sky mining cbs midnight oil 
 
blue sky mining represents an important moment in the career 
of midnight oil the record is a chance for the australian band to 
consolidate gains made with its last release the us breakthrough 
diesel and dust in 1987 
so what does midnight oil decide to sing about the environment 
malaise world unity obvious choices at a time when socially 
conscious rock is a fad 
except that midnight oil has addressed such subjects for years 
the band has always been more interested in making a point than 
making a buck the point on blue sky mining is that the worlds 
a mess if anyone cares 
often that message is eloquently stated by lead singersocial 
activist peter garrett two of the best cuts river runs red 
and blue sky mine lament that man takes from the land but 
rarely puts anything back nothings as precious as a hole in the 
ground garrett brays sarcastically in the latter 
forgotten years a variation on billy joels we didnt 
start the fire assesses the current generations place in 
history and concludes that its time to give a damn the 
desperate and divided years these should not be forgotten years 
garrett sings 
the final tracks one country and the wryly titled 
antarctica punctuate the record with two exclamation marks 
the former is a plea for global harmony the latter a plea for a 
place not yet fouled by mankind 
musically the group is more restrained than in the past for 
garrett the approach makes his words more evocative than ever but 
the muted sound which includes strings on much of side 2 robs the 
rest of the band of some of its wallop 
while ace guitarists jim moginie and martin rotsey are 
occasionally set loose the introduction to river runs red is 
glorious such instrumental peaks are frustratingly few its 
ironic that on an album so concerned about natural resources 
midnight oil wastes some of its own 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
tafelmusik by georg philipp telemann archiv musica antiqua 
koln directed by reinhard goebel 
 
if its been said that vivaldi wrote the same concerto hundreds 
of times the saying also goes that telemann wrote hundreds of 
concertos once or maybe its the other way around 
anyway this amazingly prolific contemporary of bach and handel 
composed more than 3000 pieces a bounty for the telemann fan and 
a distinctly uninteresting fact for those who prefer mozart 
beethoven or brahms 
as the fine liner notes in this typically handsome archiv 
package point out tafelmusik or banquet music was not strictly 
intended as background for meals though the modern cdowner with a 
neutral attitude to telemann may indeed put it to that use 
telemann wrote these pieces for sale to subscribers as a complete 
set 
scored for small groups of strings with variously flutes 
recorder oboes or trumpets the works are divided into three 
parts each part is subdivided into five multimovement sections 
suite quartet concert trio and solo followed by a conclusion 
tafelmusik is sort of like telemanns ring cycle 
the sections are often performed or recorded separately archiv 
does a good service by issuing them complete in four discs 
totaling more than four hours the casual listener has the benefit 
of an excellent sample of telemanns work and the connoisseur has 
a complete version of one of telemanns finest compositions 
the performance is impeccable in fact too impeccable the 
musicians playing period instruments are overly polite in their 
interpretation the flutes albeit not modern instruments have a 
timid almost boring sound some quite expressive playing though 
comes from the violins the harpsichord continuo often overbalances 
the other instruments 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
</TEXT>
