<TEXT>
the academic world has hardly finished licking 
its wounds from allan blooms runaway best seller the closing of 
the american mind 
blooms premise which fit perfectly the collegebashing mood of 
the 1980s orchestrated by former us secretary of education 
william bennett held that all was well on us campuses until the 
60s when students began asking rude questions called ancient 
verities mere opinions and even placed mick jagger and his ilk 
above blooms beloved plato and aristotle as popular icons 
now comes a more radical and even bleaker broadside aimed at 
academe killing the spirit higher education in america 
viking press 1995 by the historian page smith 
no smith says all was not well at us colleges before the 
60s any talk of the good old days simply doesnt jibe with 
the history of higher education in this country 
the crisis afflicting americas campuses is nothing new writes 
smith nor he admits are his criticisms 
he proceeds in this powerful work to add fresh and fascinating 
detail to the history of higher education what we learn is that 
from its colonial beginnings to this day the system has been 
fundamentally flawed fostering in students and teachers alike a 
leaden conformity over creativity 
and in its obeisance to the great god science college education 
has lost its direction and its soul 
im not optimistic about piecemeal reforms at this stage 
smith said in a telephone interview from his home in santa cruz 
calif where he writes a syndicated column on old age and is an 
emeritus professor at the university of californiasanta cruz 
smith was the founding provost of ucsanta cruz and author of 
numerous historical works including an eightvolume history of the 
united states 
he said he was moved to write killing the spirit after he 
learned of an aspiring college teacher who almost saw his career 
hopes derailed by his academic judges because he invoked the name 
of a german historian eugen rosenstockhuessy whose ideas were 
considered heretical 
by coincidence smith had been initially denied for graduate 
work at harvard 40 years earlier because he had studied under 
rosenstockhuessy and had similarly invoked that historians name 
to the chagrin of harvards history department 
it occurred to smith that colleges were not and never have 
been the marketplaces of ideas many believe them to be 
instead schools have long practiced what he calls academic 
fundamentalism meaning woe to any student or teacher with the 
courage to stray from the intellectual orthodoxy of the moment 
i thought my god can the academic world be that rigid that 
doctrinaire smith said indeed it can he argues 
none of academias sacred cows escapes smiths critical lance 
the tenure system requires that teachers publish mountains of 
useless research academic departments are intellectually 
stultifying and command a teachers first loyalty the lecture 
system is simply an unnatural and boring way of transmitting 
knowledge the social nonsciences and the inhuman 
humanities as smith dubs them have sold their ouls in their 
wholly unsuccessful efforts to be viewed as science with a capital 
s 
he calls anthropology arguably the funniest academic 
discipline there is something faintly ridiculous about a sober 
white anthropologist asking impertinent questions of quizzical 
aborigines and writing down the answers 
of both anthropology and sociology smith writes the 
treatment of people as objects of scrutiny scientific or not is 
when one thinks about it pretty deplorable 
psychology supposedly the study of the human psyche the soul 
has denied the existence of the soul as unscientific and in 
this soulless state smith says psychology has much to answer for 
lobotomies shock therapy involuntary drug experimentation and the 
perfection of ways to manipulate people into buying things they 
dont want or need 
history in one of its latest pseudoscientific form is called 
cliometrics by its practitioners who feed voting data property 
rolls and the like into computers one egregious result of such 
historical number crunching was a 1974 work time on the cross 
which purported to show with charts and graphs that most american 
slaves were happy and that slavery as an institution had merely 
gotten a bad press 
and economics is no more a science than the other social 
nonsciences no matter how hard it contends otherwise it 
has in the final analysis to deal with human behavior and human 
behavior remains maddeningly unpredictable fortunately smith 
writes 
and in a chapter certain to raise feminist hackles smith says 
womens studies that mushroomed on campuses since the 60s are 
clearly out of hand 
the image that women students carry away with them on 
graduation must be of a world hopelessly divided into exploiting 
males and oppressed females he writes 
professors meanwhile complain about the publish or perish 
system they also complain about their teaching load which 
over the years has grown ever lighter one wonders what these 
seemingly misanthropic souls want besides their sabbaticals 
interestingly smith singles out community colleges for praise 
teachers in such schools have a sense of mission and closeness to 
their students too often lacking in loftier institutions he says 
smiths book is descriptive in the manner of the historian it 
is no blueprint for reform it offers only the broadest 
prescription a belief in smaller more personal colleges that 
somehow reconcile the scientific with the spiritual 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lee mitgang has covered education for the 
associated press since 1981 
</TEXT>
