<TEXT>
federal officials say they are protecting 
competition by blocking gillette co from acquiring the wilkinson 
blade and razor business in the united states 
gillette officials say the federal action is not a serious 
setback insisting their main interest is in wilkinsons business 
in other parts of the world 
gillette and the us justice department announced a settlement 
monday in which gillette dropped its plans to acquire the us 
razor business of wilkinson 
the action follows statements last year by bush administration 
officials that the government intends to promote competition 
through tighter enforcement of antitrust laws 
gillette the world leader in the razor industry announced in 
december it was helping finance a buyout of wilkinsons swedish 
owner under the deal gillette said it would acquire the wilkinson 
blade and razor business outside of europe 
gillette also said it would gain nonvoting interest in the newly 
created netherlands company eemland management services bv which 
would retain the european wilkinson business as well as worldwide 
match and lighter operations 
but the justice department filed an antitrust suit in january 
saying the deal could reduce competition in the united states and 
hurt consumers 
gillette officials said that after the suit was filed the 
company indicated it would not acquire the wilkinson us business 
and under the settlement gillette agreed not to do so in the 
future 
we felt it did not violate the antitrust law we still feel it 
doesnt said david fausch a gillette spokesman but he said 
gillette did not consider wilkinsons us business large enough to 
justify a lengthy and costly court case 
gillette said the settlement would not affect any other aspect 
of the transaction wilkinsons us business will remain under the 
control of the netherlands company fausch said 
the proposed final judgment would permit wilkinson sword to 
remain an efficient and independent competitor in the united states 
market james f rill assistant us attorney general said in a 
statement 
under the proposed settlement which must be approved in court 
gillette also would be prevented from acquiring wilkinsons 
production facilities in europe that are used to supply the united 
states 
the agreement also would bar eemland from transferring 
trademarks to gillette for blades sold in the united states or 
europe furthermore it would prohibit gillette from acting as 
eemlands agent for the us razor market and would prevent 
gillette from acquiring more equity in eemland the government said 
gillette said its principal purpose was to develop the global 
potential of the wilkinson brand outside the european community and 
the united states 
