japanese people questioned in a nationwide poll 
released thursday were almost evenly split about whether us 
criticism of japans trade policy is reasonable 
the financial newspaper nihon keizai shimbun said 474 percent 
of the 6186 people who responded to the survey said they view us 
trade complaints as basically reasonable 
this included 9 percent who said they completely agree with the 
criticisms and 384 percent who replied that the us claims are 
basically right although there are a few points that seem 
unreasonable the newspaper said 
another 329 percent of the respondents said the criticism was 
unreasonable with an additional 66 percent saying the criticism 
was completely unreasonable 
another 131 percent said they could not say if the criticism 
was reasonable or did not know 
sixtythree percent of the respondents said japan should open 
its rice market at least partially to allow the sale of foreign 
rice despite government attempts to keep japans rice market 
closed the newspaper said 
it said a minority of 311 percent said absolutely no foreign 
rice should be allowed into japan 
the governments zeroimport policy is not getting firm 
public support the newspaper commented 
in current trade talks the united states has asked japan to 
revise its landuse policies to reduce the price of land 
streamline its complicated distribution system to allow easier 
access by foreign firms and boost public works spending 
japan in turn has urged the united states to reduce its 
federal budget deficit increase its savings and investment rates 
and improve worker training and education to help boost us export 
competitiveness 
the newspaper said 859 percent of respondents said japan should 
do its best to meet the us requests for reasons such as to do 
so will benefit japan or because the usjapan relationship is 
important 
younger respondents tended to be more supportive of the us 
trade pressure the newspaper said of respondents in their 20s 
919 percent said japan should respond positively to the us 
requests 
it said 769 percent replied that the two countries 
relationship would probably either improve or retain its current 
closeness in the future 
the newspaper did not provide a margin of error for the poll 
which it said was conducted march 1619 
