<TEXT>
japanese government leaders struggled tuesday to 
build a consensus before next weeks deadline for responding to 
us demands that japan foster trade by altering its economy 
at prime minister toshiki kaifus request the government has 
created a series of proposals aimed at meeting the us requests in 
recent trade talks 
the socalled structural impediments initiative talks are aimed 
at eliminating factors in each countrys economy that hinder 
reductions in their 49 billion trade imbalance 
chief cabinet secretary misoji sakamoto met party leaders in a 
series of meetings tuesday to ask for their support for the 
government proposals 
but former foreign minister shintaro abe an influential 
politician who is widely seen as a prime candidate to succeed 
kaifu reportedly warned sakamoto not to accept every us request 
japanus relations are very important and are at the core of 
japans diplomacy but we cannot say yes to every request kyodo 
news service quoted abe as saying if we accept everything it 
us demands will go on endlessly 
japan is expected to convey its decisions to the united states 
at the fourth round of the bilateral talks set for next monday and 
tuesday in washington 
the asahi shimbun a leading japanese newspaper recently 
printed a list of more than 200 suggestions made by the united 
states in the talks 
washington wants to eliminate barriers in japans economic and 
business structure that it contends prevent foreign companies from 
entering the japanese market 
for example washington says japans complex distribution system 
makes it difficult for foreign businesses to sell their products on 
the japanese market it also has pressured japan to boost its 
public works spending and tighten enforcement of its antimonopoly 
law to assure fair competition for foreign businesses 
toshio yamaguchi chairman of the governing liberal democratic 
partys panel handling issues related to the trade talks told the 
associated press that kaifu must tackle those three issues 
without hesitating to accept pain 
he needs to go as far as considering the possibility of 
scrapping the laws related to those issues he said or we may 
not be able to come up with decisions acceptable to the united 
states 
but other liberal democratic leaders were less conciliatory 
said lawmaker takujiro hamada who chaired the meeting 
the parliamentarians said that resistance to the reforms was 
very strong in their constituencies and that it would take a long 
time to carry out the reforms suggested by the united states in the 
trade talks hamada said 
separately the leading financial newspaper nihon keizai shimbun 
released results of a public opinion survey in which 474 percent 
of the 6186 respondents said they viewed the us trade complaints 
as basically reasonable 
some 9 percent said they completely agree with the demands and 
384 percent replied that the us claims basically were right but 
there were a few unreasonable points the newspaper said 
it said 329 percent said many of the us requests were 
unreasonable and 66 called them completely unreasonable 
the newspaper said 859 percent of the respondents said japan 
should do its best to meet the us requests because to do so 
will benefit japan or because the usjapan relationship is 
important no margin of error was provided for the survey 
conducted march 1619 
meanwhile government officials said tuesday they had agreed to 
start considering a us toy companys bid to open a discount store 
in japan 
toys r us has announced plans to open a 53800 squarefoot 
discount store in niigata 160 miles northwest of tokyo despite 
strong opposition by local shopkeepers 
japans largescale retail stores law one item targeted by 
us trade officials requires that small retailers be consulted 
before any large stores are opened in their areas 
while some japanese retailers have had to wait up to 10 years 
for permission to set up large new stores consideration is under 
way to shorten the maximum waiting period required under the law to 
two years said an official of the ministry of international 
trade and industry who spoke on condition of anonymity 
in addition to making entry to japans market difficult for 
foreign retailers the law works against larger japanese stores 
that would be more likely to carry foreign products us officials 
say 
