<TEXT>
xerox corp on tuesday introduced a new 
copier that can phone home for help when it senses a problem 
developing 
the xerox 5065 a midvolume copier that produces 62 copies a 
minute is the first xerox copier to offer a builtin remote 
interactive communications system the company said 
xeroxs highvolume 1090 copier offers the ric system as an 
optional addon feature said xerox spokesman daniel c minchen 
the ric system continuously checks the copiers performance 
against set standards and alerts a central computer when it notices 
a potential problem minchen said 
information about the problem is transmitted via telephone to 
the central computer where an artificial intelligence system 
analyzes the data and decides whether a service call is needed 
surveys show that customers highest priority is avoiding copier 
breakdowns and emergency maintenance calls the company said 
the ric system should notice most problems before the people 
using the machine do minchen said eliminating the need for 
customers to call xerox for service 
with every service call theres a possibility for 
dissatisfaction he said this eliminates all that by notifying 
the company before a potential problem becomes a real problem 
well call the customer first 
minchen said the ric system will not notice problems such as 
loose doors or spots on the copy but it will detect document 
misfeeds depletion of the copiers developer or toner repeated 
paper jams and other mechanical or electrical failures he said 
the artificial intelligence system decides what the problem 
might be and sends a service worker out with the right parts 
minchen said 
the system also keeps track of how many copies are made which 
minchen said will be a more efficent way of billing than requiring 
customers to keep track of how much they use a machine 
the 5065 copier will sell for 30650 xerox said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

